e%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Ffortnite-epic-games-apple-lawsuit-explained-2020-8%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EEpic%20Games%20antitrust%20case%2C%3C%2Fa%3E%20writing%20that%20they%20violated%20a%202021%20injunction%20in%20the%20case.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ERogers%2C%20in%20her%20order%2C%20wrote%20that%20Alex%20Roman%2C%20Apple's%20vice%20president%20of%20finance%2C%20%26quot%3Boutright%20lied%26quot%3B%20to%20the%20court%20while%20under%20oath%20about%20when%20Apple%20decided%20to%20impose%20a%2027%25%20commission%20fee%20on%20transactions%20facilitated%20through%20its%20App%20Store.%20Roman%20did%20not%20immediately%20respond%20to%20a%20request%20for%20comment.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BNeither%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fapple%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EApple%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20nor%20its%20counsel%2C%20corrected%20the%2C%20now%20obvious%2C%20lies%2C%26quot%3B%20Rogers%20wrote.%20%26quot%3BThey%20did%20not%20seek%20to%20withdraw%20the%20testimony%20or%20to%20have%20it%20stricken%20(although%20Apple%20did%20request%20that%20the%20Court%20strike%20other%20testimony).%20Thus%2C%20Apple%20will%20be%20held%20to%20have%20adopted%20the%20lies%20and%20misrepresentations%20to%20this%20Court.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20court%20referred%20the%20matter%20to%20the%20United%20States%20Attorney%20for%20the%20Northern%20District%20of%20California%20%26quot%3Bto%20investigate%20whether%20criminal%20contempt%20proceedings%20are%20appropriate.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20ruling%20stems%20from%20a%20case%20brought%20against%20Apple%20by%20the%20video%20game%20developer%20Epic%20Games%20in%202020%2C%20in%20which%20Epic%20Games%20accused%20Apple%20of%20engaging%20in%3Cstrong%3E%20%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fgoogle-epic-games-case-antitrust-law-2024-10%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eanticompetitive%20practices%3C%2Fa%3E%20related%20to%20its%20control%20over%20the%20App%20Store%20and%20in-app%20payment%20systems.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIn%202021%2C%20following%20a%20trial%2C%20the%20court%20ruled%20that%20Apple's%20restrictions%20on%20in-app%20purchasing%20methods%20outside%20the%20one%20offered%20by%20the%20App%20Store%20were%20indeed%20anticompetitive.%20The%20ruling%20largely%20favored%20Apple%2C%20finding%20that%20the%20company%20had%20engaged%20in%20anticompetitive%20behavior%20in%20only%20one%20of%2010%20counts.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20Court%20then%20issued%20an%20injunction%20forcing%20Apple%20to%20allow%20developers%20to%20inform%20users%20about%20external%20purchasing%20options%2C%C2%A0but%20Rogers%20says%20the%20company%20refused%20to%20comply%20with%20the%20injunction.%20She%20wrote%20that%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BApple's%20response%20to%20the%20Injunction%20strains%20credulity%2C%26quot%3B%20Rogers%20wrote%20in%20the%20Wednesday%20filing.%20%26quot%3BAfter%20two%20sets%20of%20evidentiary%20hearings%2C%20the%20truth%20emerged.%20Apple%2C%20despite%20knowing%20its%20obligations%20thereunder%2C%20thwarted%20the%20Injunction's%20goals%2C%20and%20continued%20its%20anticompetitive%20conduct%20solely%20to%20maintain%20its%20revenue%20stream.%20Remarkably%2C%20Apple%20believed%20that%20this%20Court%20would%20not%20see%20through%20its%20obvious%20cover-up.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAn%20Apple%20spokesperson%20told%20Business%20Insider%20that%20the%20company%20%26quot%3Bstrongly%26quot%3B%20disagrees%20with%20the%20court's%20decision.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BWe%20will%20comply%20with%20the%20court's%20order%2C%20and%20we%20will%20appeal%2C%26quot%3B%20the%20spokesperson%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%3ERead%20the%20original%20article%20on%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fjudge-finds-apple-executive-lied-under-oath-refers-criminal-investigation-2025-4%5C%22%3EBusiness%20Insider%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1746072121000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F6812c875a4